      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: serialize outbound deliveries per channel+recipient",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nWhen multiple sessions (main + sub-agent) send messages to the same recipient concurrently, replies can arrive out of order because each session's delivery call races independently on the channel's HTTP endpoint. Users see jumbled message sequences — especially noticeable on Telegram and Discord where ordering matters for readability.\n\n**Reproduction:** Run a main agent and sub-agent that both reply to the same user within a short window. Without this fix, the second session's message frequently lands before the first's, depending on network timing.\n\n**Fix:** Introduces a `DeliverySerializer` that chains concurrent deliveries to the same `channel:accountId:recipient` key in FIFO order while keeping different recipients fully concurrent. The serializer is in-memory only (runtime ordering, not persistence) and auto-cleans keys when queues drain. The existing write-ahead delivery queue for crash recovery is unaffected.\n\nA follow-up commit wraps `fn()` in `Promise.resolve().then()` so a synchronous throw is converted to a rejection rather than hanging the result promise forever (addresses review feedback).\n\nIncludes tests for ordering, concurrency across targets, error propagation, sync-throw handling, and queue cleanup.\n\nRebased to 2026.3.13.\n\n---\n\n## Real behavior proof — Telegram, live session (2026-05-22)\n\nThis race was observed live in production during this PR's own review session on **Telegram** (not Signal).\n\n**What happened:** During a single agent turn handling `pr view 44143`, two outbound messages were sent in sequence to the same Telegram recipient (`telegram:6194445555`):\n1. A long ClawSweeper analysis dump (~4KB)\n2. A summary message referencing and synthesizing that analysis\n\n**Observed:** The summary (message 2) arrived visibly before the analysis (message 1) in the Telegram chat. The recipient had to read the synthesis before the content it was synthesizing — the exact inversion this PR fixes.\n\n**Context:** Telegram direct message, same `channel:accountId:to` key, single agent session, two sends within the same turn. No sub-agent involved — the race can happen within a single session turn when one send is large enough to lose the HTTP timing race against a smaller follow-up send.\n\n**Telegram message IDs at time of observation:** user message `5519` (\"we're experiencing that right now here in Telegram. Look at your last 3 messages\"), preceded by the two inverted agent messages. Timestamp: 2026-05-22 ~15:00 EDT.\n\nThis confirms the bug is not Signal-specific and reproduces on Telegram in normal production usage without any artificial test setup.",
